                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><strong>Triceps Lateral Heads</strong></h3><p>The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536996/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">triceps lateral head</a> originates from the back of the humerus (upper arm bone) and inserts into the forearm at the elbow. It supports the elbow joint, primarily when extending it from a flexed (bent) position.</p><p>During the extension phase, the lateral head works against the dumbbell’s resistance to straighten the elbow and stabilize the joint. This <a href="https://www.thieme-connect.de/products/ejournals/html/10.1055/a-1664-8701" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">time under tension</a> increases the muscle’s engagement.</p><h3><strong>Wrist Extensors</strong></h3><p>The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534805/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">wrist extensor</a> muscles originate near the lateral epicondyle and are inserted into the base of the forearm. They stabilize and extend the wrist and fingers during daily hand movements.</p><p>These muscles engage during dumbbell single-arm tricep extensions to firmly grip the dumbbell during the eccentric (muscle lengthening) phase. They also provide support to maintain controlled movement and stabilize the wrist, preventing overextension injuries.</p><p>If you notice wrist pain or discomfort, stop exercising immediately and seek the help of a medical professional.</p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
